<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="370" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,764,977,1380]" pageId="11" pageNumber="370">
This species was previously recorded from Liberian and Guinean 
<collectingRegion box="[408,488,1011,1037]" country="Liberia" name="Nimba" pageId="11" pageNumber="370">Nimba</collectingRegion>
(Wolton 
<emphasis box="[610,668,1011,1037]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="370">et al</emphasis>
., 1982; 
<bibRefCitation author="BROSSET, A." box="[151,315,1045,1071]" pageId="11" pageNumber="370" pagination="545 - 555" refId="ref12002" refString="BROSSET, A. 1985 [for 1984]. Chiropteres d'altitude du Mont Nimba (Guinee). Description d'une espece nouvelle, Hipposideros lamottei. Mammalia, 48: 545 - 555." type="journal article" year="1985">Brosset, 1985</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="FAHR, J. &amp; B. A. DJOSSA &amp; H. VIERHAUS" box="[327,523,1045,1071]" pageId="11" pageNumber="370" pagination="245 - 247" refId="ref13222" refString="FAHR, J., B. A. DJOSSA, and H. VIERHAUS. 2006. Rapid assessment of bats (Chiroptera) in Dere, Diecke and Mt. Bero classified forests, southeastern Guinea; including a review of the distribution of bats in Guinee Forestiere. Pp. 168 - 180, 245 - 247, in A rapid biological assessment of three classified forests in Southeastern Guinea (H. E. WRIGHT, J. MCCULLOUGH, L. E. ALONSO, and M. S. DIALLO, eds.). Conservation International, RAP Bulletin of Biological Assessment, Washington, D. C., 40, 248 pp." type="book chapter" year="2006">
Fahr 
<emphasis box="[387,438,1045,1071]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="370">et al</emphasis>
., 2006
</bibRefCitation>
). During this survey, it was recorded widely in forested and forest edge habitats between 450 and 
<quantity box="[462,538,1114,1140]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.3" pageId="11" pageNumber="370" unit="m" value="530.0">530 m</quantity>
a.s.l. This taxon is distributed across much of sub-Saharan Africa, occurring in a wide range of habitats and exhibiting significant morphological variation (
<bibRefCitation author="HAPPOLD, M." box="[568,753,1217,1243]" pageId="11" pageNumber="370" pagination="639 - 642" refId="ref13555" refString="HAPPOLD, M. 2013 b. Pipistrellus nanus Banana pipistrellus (Banana bat). Pp. 639 - 642, in The mammals of Africa. Volume IV: Hedgehogs, shrews and bats (M. HAPPOLD and D. C. D. HAPPOLD, eds). Bloomsbury Publishing, London, 800 pp." type="book chapter" year="2013">
Happold, 2013 
<emphasis box="[739,753,1217,1243]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="370">b</emphasis>
</bibRefCitation>
) suggesting the presence of cryptic species. This species displayed rather large variation in size at Mt 
<collectingRegion box="[151,231,1319,1345]" country="Liberia" name="Nimba" pageId="11" pageNumber="370">Nimba</collectingRegion>
(forearm range 25.6–30.0 mm), but the significance of this has yet to be investigated.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
